@NODE HOWTO "How to work with midiIn"
@PREV INSTALL
@NEXT DEALING

                         ########################
                         How to work with midiIn?
                         ########################
@WORDWRAP

   At the bottom of the midiIn window there are 30 small squares. They
represent 30 independent banks. Each bank may contain one sample and has
it's own parameters. To edit the specific bank's parameters You have to
choose the bank either by clicking on it's small gadget, or with Amiga
keyboard, using the <- -> cursor or numeric keys. The current bank is
highlighted. All non-empty banks change their color, too.
   You can Copy, Paste and Delete (clear all data) banks by using the
corresponding entries from the Edit menu.

The parameters are:

 - Audio chan - LEFT, RIGHT or ANY. Two first don't need explanation,
   ANY means that the sample is played on the first free channel (left or
   right)

* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}: midiIn plays samples in 14 bit resolution. Therefore it needs two
physical Amiga channels to play one sample, so only two samples can be
played simultaneusly. The new version will use AHI and its own mixing
routines to play more samples in 14/16 bits. See @{"technical specifications" LINK TECH 23}@{ub}

 - Midi chan - the MIDI channel assigned to this bank.

 - Bank priority - samples with lower priority mute samples with higher
   priority. It means that if a sample is being played and it has
   priority set to 3 then if the MIDI NoteOn message comes and there are
   no free channels (or rather no free channel in this version ;) then the
   new sample's priority must be 3 or less. If it's more than 3, the sample
   is not played. You can control this value with the UP and DOWN cursor
   keys on the Amiga keyboard.

 - duration

   ON->OFF means that the sample is played as long as You keep the key on
   Your MIDI keyboard pressed. This is natural.
   ON->ON means that to stop the sample You have to press the same key
   again. It's good especially for long, looped samples - You don't have
   to keep the key pressed.

 - Loop - if the gadget is checked, the sample is looped. The loop range
   is always imported from 8SVX files.

 - Base - the note being a base note of the sample. You choose it by
   pressing the SET gadget nearby and pressing the required key on MIDI
   keyboard or pointing it with mouse. The current base note will flash
   during editing. 
   When editing the base note be careful not to feed Amiga with random MIDI
   notes for example from sequencer, because it all affects the base note!
   If You play the sample above its base note it will sound higher, below
   the base note it will sound lower. It's easy and natural.

 - Fine tune - here You can tune Your samples. Maximum negative tune means
   1/2 tone lower, maximum positive tune means 1/2 tone higher.

 - The very important parameter is RANGE. To edit this very important 
   parameter You have to check the Edit range gadget below the keyboard.
   Some part of the keyboard will turn blue (or whatever colour You have
   assigned in Your WB). It means that the sample will play ONLY in this
   range of keyboard. It is very handy if You want to split Your keboard
   to play different samples on different octaves, for example.

   You can edit the range with mouse or with MIDI keyboard. Check out how
   it works exactly. If there are any banks on the same MIDI channel,
   their range is shown as a blue stripe in the upper part of the keyboard.
   The small gadgets representing these banks turns blue also.
   If the ranges cover each other and the MIDI channel is the same, the
   sample with higher priority will be played.

   When You finish editing the range, press the Edit range gadget again to
   leave the edit mode.

   When editing the range be careful not to feed Amiga with random MIDI
   notes for example from sequencer, because it all affects the range!
* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}:
To avoid affecting your work, because of accidental MIDI notes, just click
on the Midi control gadget (uncheck it). It is placed in the upper-right
corner of the main window.@{ub}

The Instrument List

   It is a list on the right part of midiIn window. To assign a sample to
a bank You have to load it to the list first. The sample from the list can
be assigned to any number of banks.
   To load a sample to the list click on the Add gadget below the list. A
standard @{"file-requester" LINK INSTALL 35} will appear. Now select the samples You want to
load (multi-select option is available with shift key).
   The current version of midiIn recognises the @{"8SVX" LINK TECH 53} (also 16 bit) and
@{"AIFF" LINK TECH 53} samples (2-32 bits, any number of channels). Trying to load different
sample formats will fail.

* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}: The samples are NOT loaded to memory now. They are loaded when You
assign them to specific banks. Of course if You assign one sample to more
than one bank, the sample is loaded to memory only once.
The name of new sample is compared with names in the list and in case of
same names loading is not performed. You don't have to worry then about
having the same sample twice in the list.@{ub}

   To remove the sample from the list click on the Delete gadget below the
Instrument list and then double-click on the samples You want to remove.
To leave the Delete mode click on the Delete gadget again.

   To assign a sample to an empty bank just select the bank and click on
the sample's name on the list. The sample will be loaded to memory now. If
there's not enough free memory a requester will apprear.

* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}: Samples are stored in any free (PUBLIC) memory. This allows You to
have them as many as Your board permits (128 MB with Cyberstorm... or more)@{ub}


 To free the bank click on the Free gadget near the Instrument (sample)
name field.     

   To clear the Instrument List press the Clear gadget. midiIn will ask
You then if You want to clear all samples, the unused samples (the ones
that are not used in any bank), or You changed Your mind.


   There are two important gadgets in the upper right corner of the midiIn
window:
 - the Audio gadget allocates and frees the audio channels.
 - the Midi control gadget turns on/off the external MIDI
   keyboard/sequencer control of midiIn. 

   These gadgets can be also controlled by Audio enable and Midi control
entries from the Settings menu.

   If these two gadgets are active, You can perform. midiIn waits for MIDI
NoteOn and NoteOff messages and plays samples as You assigned them.
If only the Audio gadged is checked, you can alternatively play sample
in current bank by clicking on the keyboard gadget or pressing [<-\] (return)
key.

@ENDNODE
@NODE DEALING "Dealing with projects"
@PREV HOWTO
@NEXT MENUS

                       #####################
                       Dealing with projects
                       #####################
@WORDWRAP

   To begin a new project just double click on midiIn icon ;)
   After loading the program is ready to work. You may be surprised
that @{"Instrument List" LINK HOWTO 83} may contain some samples - don't worry,
everything is OK, You must have @{"saved settings" LINK MENUS 38} with these samples in
the List. They are now default. You can always clear the list and
save settings again.
   To clear the current project and start the new one choose the @{"New entry" LINK MENUS 9}
from Project menu. It will free all samples from memory and
reset all banks' settings. If the current project is unsaved (it
should have an asterisk (*) by it's name on midiIn window's drag
bar) midiIn will ask You if You really want to loose it.
   
   Projects are saved by default in the PROGDIR:projects/ directory.
You can change this by saving a project in a different place and
saving settings. The new path will be saved then.

   Projects do not contain the sound data (samples). They just
contain the sample path and filename.  Therefore they can be kept
anywhere (they don't need special big partitions).

   To load a project from disk select @{"Open" LINK MENUS 10}. A standard @{"file requester" LINK INSTALL 35}
will appear.
   When You choose the project file, midiIn will load it and then
try to load all samples assigned to banks. The name and type of
currently loaded sample is shown on midiIn window's drag bar. If the
sample cannot be found, a requester appears asking You if You want
to replace this sample with another one (choose which one...), abort
loading, or skip to the next sample.
* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}:  When changing the sample path in file requester window, the next
sample will be loaded from the directory you have chosen. So the best
thing is to keep all the samples assigned to one project in the same
directory.  It is only important for people who often move files from
one directory to another to keep their harddrive clean.@{ub}

   To save a project to disk choose Save from the @{"Project menu" LINK MENUS 7}. If
Your project is new ("untitled"), a filerequester will appear asking
You for project's path and filename. Just write it down and strike the 
"OK" button.

@ENDNODE
@NODE MENUS "Menus"
@PREV DEALING
@NEXT ADVANCED

                                  #####
                                  Menus
                                  #####

@WORDWRAP

   Project
   ^^^^^^^
    -> New - @{"Prepares a new projects" LINK DEALING 12}
    -> Open - @{"loads a project from disk" LINK DEALING 26}
    -> Save - saves the project with the current name
              there is the project name displayed on the midiIn window's
              drag bar; if it is followed by an asterisk (*) it means that
              the project is changed and You have to save it to store the
              changes
    -> Save as - saves the project opening a @{"file-requester" LINK INSTALL 35} allowing You
                 to change the path and the name of the project
    -> About - displays information about the authors and some important
               data: number of loaded samples, memory allocated by them,
               free memory available and the time you are working with midiIn.
    -> Quit - quits midiIn; if the project is unsaved midiIn asks You for
              confirmation

   Edit
   ^^^^ 
    -> Copy - copies the current bank to buffer
    -> Paste - pastes buffer to current bank
    -> Delete - clears all data in current bank
         see @{"How to work with midiIn" LINK HOWTO 6} for details

   Settings
   ^^^^^^^^
    -> Audio enable - allocates and frees audio.device
    -> Midi control - allows/permits MIDI control of midiIn
         see @{"How to work with midiIn" LINK HOWTO 122} for details
    -> Advanced - opens a @{"special window" LINK ADVANCED 6} in which You can change
                  the midi.library and sound player parameters
    -> Save settings - saves @{"sound preferences" LINK ADVANCED 12}, @{"default paths" LINK DEALING 18}
                       to projects and samples and default @{"Instrument (sample) List" LINK HOWTO 83}
                       in file 'PROGDIR:midiIn.pref'

@ENDNODE
@NODE ADVANCED "Advanced settings"
@PREV MENUS
@NEXT TECH

                         #################
                         Advanced settings
                         #################
@WORDWRAP

  As soon as you choose the @{"Advanced..." LINK MENUS 36} option from the menu "settings"
new window appears. It allows you to change sound parameters and
MIDI messages source.  There should be no threat to the system stability
while experimenting with these, but it is always best to know what
exactly you are doing.

The sound parameters:

The string gadget displays the current @{"replay DMA frequency" LINK TECH 23}
The slider below is connected to it and contains the DMA period. The higher
the frequency (lower period), the better quality of sound. But maximum value
is limited by the screen mode of your public screen. On a PAL/NTSC/Euro36
(15 kHz) screens the rate is up to 28000 Hz. On doublescan modes
(MULTISCAN/Euro72/Super72/DBLPAL/DBLNTSC) it's doubled. So, if you wish
to play sound with a better than CD quality e.g. 48000 Hz you must have
a multiscan (or VGA) monitor attached to your Amiga.

The cycle gadget below lets you choose the size of @{"chip RAM buffer" LINK TECH 23}
Generally this should be big (up to 128 kB).  Thanx to this, interrupts
happen rarelier.  On slower Amigas (especially without FastRAM) it may
cause periodical locking of the system.  You should lower this parameter to
about 2048 bytes on a bare A1200.  The interrupts will happen more often,
but smaller chunks of memory will be transfered.
However, if buffer is too small for faster processors, sound may be distorted.
You have to experiment and find the proper value for Your hardware.

The Led/Filter checkbox enables or disables the audio Low-Pass filter.

New sound settings take effect next time a sample is being played. The
"Undo" button brings back the same parameters that this window was
opened with.

The MIDI source:

Two gadgets, "Prev" and "Next", allow you to change the source of incoming
@{"MIDI messages" LINK TECH 43}. They browse through the midi.library public source list.
If no other midi related program is in memory only "MidiIn" will be available.
"MidiIn" is any external midi keyboard/sequencer connected to Amiga serial
port (with midi interface).
This option gives midiIn (the program:) possibility to act as a sample
player for any Amiga program that also uses midi.library like virtual keyboards
or some sequencers.

@ENDNODE
@NODE TECH "Technical specifications"
@PREV ADVANCED
@NEXT AUTORS

                        ########################
                        Technical specifications
                        ########################
@WORDWRAP

* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}: This program requires at least Amiga OS 2.1 (V37+) to work. However
  OS 3.0 (V39+) is recommended.@{ub}

   MidiIn was compiled with @{"Amiga E v3.2e" LINK LEGAL} (thanks Wouter). The program
consists of two independent codes. First one is responsible for handling
samples (loading and playing) and the second makes up GUI and performs all
other functions. The relation between them is Object Oriented.
Each time sample is loaded the new object is being created. Every access
to it is performed through a few simple methods and therefore makes the whole
program simplier and easier to develop. Each code was made up of several
modules which were separately tested. That allowed the increasing complexity
of the program not to overgrowth me.
The GUI is also Object Oriented because of the way EasyGUI 3.33 works.
I also used the IFFParser_OO - written By Fabio Rotondo.
The program initiates a separate task to deal with midi messages, so
you can play music and operate with the program (like loading new samples)
at the same time.
The most important part is the replayer routine. It joins two physical 8 bit
channels to one with 14 bit resolution. So we have only two channels instead
of four but with better sound quality. Samples can be stored in fast RAM and
they are always treated as 16 bit data. While playing sound the sample data is
being transferred to buffer in chip RAM where audio DMA can access it. The
frequency of DMA is set to constant value, which can be @{"regulated" LINK ADVANCED 14} by
the user. Different sound frequencies are obtained by routine which transfers
audio data to chip RAM and resamples it in real time. There is no practical 
limit on how low or how hi you can really play them. Check for yourself.

* @{b}@{u}NOTE@{uu}: This version of midiIn doesn't have the VOLUME option. Therefore
        samples  are  played  with  maximum  level.  If You want to set
        volume, use external sample editors like @{"SoundFx" LINK INTRO 63}.  I know it's not
        very handy, but it's going to change in future versions.@{ub}

Currently I am testing a new routine that will allow simultanous play of
32 (16 bit) audio channnels with full volume and panoraming control for
each of them. It will be part of midiIn since next version (2.0+).
I also plan to add AHI support for sound card compatibility.

That's about playing but what about MIDI? (Musical Instrument Digital Interface)

The idea of using midi.library has one simple reason. It is easy to implement.
I don't have to worry about serial device because MIDI library has to do it
for me. The way it works permits other programs to use MIDI at the same time.
It also allows to share or exchange MIDI messages between programs. So
to work with "midiIn" you don't have to use external keyboards or sequencers.
Instead you can use any sequencer/keys emulation program that also supports
midi.library. See @{"advanced settings" LINK ADVANCED 38}.

Supported formats of sample files as for now are Audio IFF (by Apple corp.)
and IFF 8SVX (by Electronic Arts) with unreferenced extension of 16 bit data.
The SoundFX program by Stefan Kost recognizes and can store such 8SVX files
(do not confuse it with 16VX format!). I can easily add support of new formats
(the way it works is Object Oriented too), but I need some @{"feedback" LINK AUTORS} from You
if you really need them. I can also add sound datatypes support if there
are any 16 bit sound datatypes.

Stereo samples are loaded, but they are played mono.  Depending on the
Audio chan assign, left or right channel is played.

The program was tested on following systems:

- A1200 + Blizzard 1260 50Mhz + OS 3.1 (v40) + 16 MB Fast RAM
- A1200 + MTek 1230 42 Mhz + OS 3.0 (v39) + 8 MB Fast RAM
- A1200 (EC020 14Mhz) OS 3.0 without Fast RAM.

It wasn't tested on any 68000/010, OS 2.1 Amigas but should work, however there
is no @{"guarantee" LINK LEGAL} that it will.

 @{"Royal" LINK AUTORS 3}.

@ENDNODE
